      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why N-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>With six tiles in the bag, N is the second most common consonant after S. You'll have at least one N on your rack for most of the game. While N itself is only worth 1 point, its frequency means you need to know how to use it effectively — otherwise it just takes up rack space that could hold higher-value tiles.</p>
      <p>The strongest N-words combine N with Z (NUZZLE at 25 points, NOZZLE at 24 points) or X (NIX at 10 points, NEXUS at 12 points). N also serves as an excellent suffix letter — adding -N or -EN to existing words extends plays cheaply. The key is knowing when to play N immediately versus holding it for a bigger combination.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing N-Words</h2>
      <p>N is everywhere in Scrabble, which means strategy matters more than memorisation. Here's how to play N effectively:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>N + Z is premium:</strong> NUZZLE (25 points) and NOZZLE (24 points) are among the highest-scoring 6-letter words in the game. When you hold N and see Z on your rack, look for these plays immediately.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>NIX is your go-to short play:</strong> At 10 points for 3 letters, NIX is compact and powerful. It fits in tight spaces and scores well on letter-bonus squares.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use N as a suffix builder:</strong> -ING, -TION, -EN, -AN, -IN — N enables dozens of suffixes. Extending existing board words with N-based suffixes is often more profitable than playing a standalone N-word.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't hoard N tiles:</strong> Drawing two or three N's cripples your rack. Play at least one immediately if you have multiples — rack balance is worth more than holding for a perfect N-word.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Two-letter N-words for parallels:</strong> NA, NE, NO, and NU are all valid. These enable parallel plays where you form multiple words simultaneously by placing tiles adjacent to existing rows.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">N-Word Patterns Worth Memorising</h2>
      <p>These productive N-word patterns help you spot scoring opportunities faster during timed play:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>N + Z words:</strong> NUZZLE, NOZZLE, NAZE — when N meets Z, points follow. These are must-know combinations</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>N + X words:</strong> NIX, NIXED, NIXING, NEXUS, NEXT — the NX combination is tight, powerful, and common enough to recall under pressure</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>NY- words:</strong> NYMPH, NYLON — pair N with Y's 4 points for above-average scores from common words</span></li>
      </ul>

